## Control Layer Architecture

The Control Layer is a shared service layer — NOT feature-specific code scattered across components.

```
src/control/
├── index.ts                    # Public API: checkApproval(), startSLA(), handleException()
├── approvals/                  # Approval engine
├── sla/                        # SLA engine
├── exceptions/                 # Exception handling
├── rules/                      # Generic rule evaluation
├── pipeline/                   # Stage rules + document requirements
├── handoff/                    # Handoff validation
└── versioning/                 # Workflow version management
```

**Usage pattern — every feature checks with Control Layer before acting:**

```typescript
// Example: moving a deal to next stage
async function moveDealToStage(dealId: string, newStageId: string) {
  // 1. Check stage entry rules
  const entryCheck = await control.checkStageEntry(dealId, newStageId);
  if (!entryCheck.allowed) {
    return { blocked: true, reason: entryCheck.missingRequirements };
  }

  // 2. Check if approval is required
  const approvalCheck = await control.checkApproval('deal_stage_change', { dealId, newStageId });
  if (approvalCheck.required) {
    await control.requestApproval(approvalCheck.flowId, { dealId, newStageId });
    return { pending_approval: true };
  }

  // 3. Execute the stage change
  await updateDealStage(dealId, newStageId);

  // 4. Start SLA timer for new stage (if configured)
  await control.startSLATimer(dealId, newStageId);

  // 5. Stop SLA timer for previous stage
  await control.stopSLATimer(dealId, previousStageId);
}
```

